s of the western frontier, the fractures visible in the American story at a mid-century history themed amusement park. The study culminates in a look at the successes and limitations of the American Girl Company empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aChild consumerszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aChildrenzUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aMaterial culturezUnited States. 0aNational characteristics, AmericanxHistory. 0aToy industryzUnited StatesxMarketing. 0aToysxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  atoy, toys, toy industry, children, children’s cultural products, American identity, American children, citizenship, twentieth century, governmental interventions, Cold War, Cold War stories, western frontier, American Girl Company, American Girl, dolls, themed amusement parks, amusement parks, American Toy Industry, Clark Doll Study, Clark Doll, Antique Dolls, childhood, Landmark Books, books, Freedomland, family, fun, family fun, history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073913840uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197882211540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978822115423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978822115/original  a978-3-11-073913-8  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK